Today, I had the honor of formally presenting long-overdue medals to the family of WWII hero Daniel Hall, a young man who never returned home and whose service went unrecognized for decades. Private Hall was drafted into the military directly out of high school, and in September 1944, he was declared Missing in Action and later Killed in Action. Thanks to the perseverance of his loved ones and the diligent work of our staff, his ultimate sacrifice is now rightfully honored.

Among the decorations presented were the Bronze Star Medal, Purple Heart, European-African-Middle Eastern Campaign Medal, World War II Victory Medal, Combat Infantryman Badge (1st Award), and the Honorable Service Lapel Button (WWII).

Today, Catholics celebrate the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, when Mary was taken into Heaven, body and soul, at the end of her life on Earth. In Italy, this August holiday has even older roots, dating back to Emperor Augustus in 18 B.C. The name Ferragosto comes from the Latin Feriae Augusti, meaning the festivals of Augustus, a time for rest and celebration.

For generations, August was when most Italians took their ferie, or vacation. Years ago, shops and offices would close on August 1, and families would spend the month at the beach, in the mountains, or in the countryside. Cities would grow quiet, and finding an open store was rare. Today, vacations may be shorter, but August 15 remains the heart of summer and a cherished national holiday.
